text: Yeah. And that happens a lot. It always seems like on these boards, there's one person that seems to have a little more experience than the others on a particular subject and kind of leads the group to making the decision. The only way you could really counter that, and again, you got to be very polite, right? Because they may not be at your level of understanding, so you can't be condescending or any of those things. But the beauty of a management committee or an oversight committee is it's typically made up of a bunch of different functional groups. And even though the guy who has a little bit of experience and really wants to lead the charge on the decision, he's typically in one group. So if you can more readily relate the topic that you're talking about across the different functions, so they understand how it fits into their pocket, I think you get away from that a lot more. And an example of that is very simply, there's always this loggerhead. going on between the balance sheet and the income statement at a sponsor who has a big pension. The balance sheet is always looking for immunize this thing. I don't want any volatility on my balance sheet. And then the income statement guy, because the accounting rules in the US are like, I don't care what you do. You just get me a 10% return because that flows through my EPS. And if I get those numbers, we're going to look good. So when you're presenting something, if you can do it from both their perspectives, so you understand where they're coming from, I think it helps a lot. And it entitles the person that really knows their stuff within their cross-functional group to really relate and speak to you about it. It's not always easy to do. And at times it's not possible to do depending on the subject matter. But I always go into these meetings trying to be able to relate it across so that group think doesn't dominate as much as it could in the past.
